sion of the harvest and extract the state-defined surplus. To provide the reader with a clearer sense of the evolution of peasant-state relations over almost a forty-year period and to highlight the dramatic changes that have taken place since 1978,1 have divided my analysis into two parts: Chapters 2 through 7 are on Maoist China, and chapters 8 and 9 are on post-Mao China. The first part examines the state's grain policies and patterns of local politics that emerged during the highly collectivized Maoist period, when the state closed free grain markets and established the system of unified purchase and sales (tonggou tongxiao). The second part describes the new methods for the production and division of the harvest after 1978, when the government decollectivized agriculture and abolished its unified procurement program.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCollective farmszChina. 0aCommunes (China) 0aCommunismzChina. 0aElite (Social sciences)zChina. 0aGrain tradexGovernment policyzChina. 0aLocal governmentzChina. 0aPeasantsxGovernment policyzChina. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh  a1970s.  aacademic.  aagriculture.  aanalysis.  aasia.  aasian history.  achinese history.  aclass structure.  aclass system.  acollectivism.  aculture.  adynasty.  afood production.  aharvest.  ainternational history.  alocal politics.  amaoist china.  amaoist period.  apeasant.  apolitical.  apolitics.  aproduction.  ascholarly.  asmall town.  asocial studies.  avillage.  aworld history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z978311063534840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052091189540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520911895423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520911895/